31
00:01:00,680 --> 00:01:02,720
So Kavya's first question.

32
00:01:02,720 --> 00:01:04,480
I have been trying to implement QC

33
00:01:04,480 --> 00:01:06,040
on my Cell Painting images

34
00:01:06,040 --> 00:01:08,320
using features from Measure Image Quality.

35
00:01:08,320 --> 00:01:10,600
I've been using PCA on the measured features.

36
00:01:10,600 --> 00:01:12,440
I seem to have measured about 107.

37
00:01:12,440 --> 00:01:14,080
And it seems like one of my cell types

38
00:01:14,080 --> 00:01:15,680
is consistently different from the other

39
00:01:15,680 --> 00:01:17,920
based on local focus score features.

40
00:01:17,920 --> 00:01:19,040
What does this mean?

41
00:01:19,040 --> 00:01:21,880
How do I interpret what some of these features mean?

42
00:01:21,880 --> 00:01:22,880
Yes.

43
00:01:22,880 --> 00:01:23,720
Yeah.

44
00:01:23,720 --> 00:01:24,560
And that's a great question.

45
00:01:24,560 --> 00:01:26,920
Because what do features mean in general

46
00:01:26,920 --> 00:01:28,040
can be really difficult,

47
00:01:28,040 --> 00:01:29,760
but it can be especially difficult

48
00:01:29,760 --> 00:01:31,400
for some of these things like image quality.

49
00:01:31,400 --> 00:01:33,440
And some of them get a little mathy.

50
00:01:33,440 --> 00:01:34,280
Yeah.

51
00:01:35,200 --> 00:01:37,040
So when in doubt,

52
00:01:37,040 --> 00:01:40,480
I always start with going to the CellProfiler manual.

53
00:01:40,480 --> 00:01:42,360
And this is the same exact information

54
00:01:42,360 --> 00:01:44,360
that's in the CellProfiler module help.

55
00:01:44,360 --> 00:01:47,080
So if you pull up the CellProfiler module help,

56
00:01:47,080 --> 00:01:50,960
you will find all the same exact text

57
00:01:50,960 --> 00:01:53,360
that's actually built from the same exact thing.

58
00:01:54,200 --> 00:02:01,200
So there's a few different kinds of quality measurements

59
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:04,240
that CellProfiler makes in Measure Image Quality.

60
00:02:04,240 --> 00:02:05,920
I'm going to start with some of the easier ones

61
00:02:05,920 --> 00:02:06,920
to talk about,

62
00:02:06,920 --> 00:02:11,600
which are not the blur ones that were in the original question,

63
00:02:11,600 --> 00:02:13,920
but just because it's important to sort of mention them.

64
00:02:13,920 --> 00:02:17,920
The intensity metrics can tell you again,

65
00:02:17,920 --> 00:02:20,120
like how much intensity is going on.

66
00:02:20,120 --> 00:02:21,720
And generally speaking,

67
00:02:21,720 --> 00:02:23,480
that's not going to be a problem,

68
00:02:23,480 --> 00:02:26,560
but these are great metrics for seeing

69
00:02:26,560 --> 00:02:29,040
if some of your images are really different from the others.

70
00:02:29,040 --> 00:02:31,640
So maybe they have a different maximum or a different minimum,

71
00:02:31,640 --> 00:02:34,880
or maybe there's some accident of metadata going on

72
00:02:34,880 --> 00:02:36,160
and they're scaled differently.

73
00:02:36,160 --> 00:02:38,320
That would be potentially really dangerous.

74
00:02:38,320 --> 00:02:43,440
So these aren't ones that are going to be good

75
00:02:43,440 --> 00:02:45,800
for checking things like, you know, is my image blurry,

76
00:02:45,800 --> 00:02:47,680
but they might indicate sort of overall problems

77
00:02:47,680 --> 00:02:50,800
with maybe you've accidentally mixed in some eight-bit images

78
00:02:50,800 --> 00:02:53,040
with your 16-bit images or something like that.

79
00:02:55,680 --> 00:02:57,520
Threshold metrics.

80
00:02:57,520 --> 00:03:01,720
So Threshold, CellProfiler can calculate the thresholds

81
00:03:01,720 --> 00:03:03,720
as part of the Measure Image Quality module

82
00:03:03,720 --> 00:03:07,400
for a bunch of the different thresholding methods that it uses.

83
00:03:07,400 --> 00:03:10,920
And again, no individual threshold is wrong,

84
00:03:10,920 --> 00:03:12,960
but it can help you see if there are patterns

85
00:03:12,960 --> 00:03:15,360
where the thresholds are consistently different

86
00:03:15,360 --> 00:03:18,080
between, you know, for a particular set of images,

87
00:03:18,080 --> 00:03:19,760
where is the threshold being set?

88
00:03:21,800 --> 00:03:24,040
Saturation metrics.

89
00:03:24,040 --> 00:03:29,720
So what fraction of the images,

90
00:03:29,720 --> 00:03:30,920
of the pixels in your image,

91
00:03:30,920 --> 00:03:33,120
are either the maximal possible value

92
00:03:33,120 --> 00:03:36,160
or the minimal possible value?

93
00:03:36,160 --> 00:03:38,520
Because if you're at the ends of the spectrum,

94
00:03:38,520 --> 00:03:41,080
you're no longer measuring quantitatively, right?

95
00:03:41,080 --> 00:03:43,000
And so at that point, like,

96
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:45,120
there could be lower signal or higher signal

97
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:47,600
and you've lost the ability to detect it.

98
00:03:47,680 --> 00:03:51,960
So no, trying to keep as little of your image as possible

99
00:03:51,960 --> 00:03:55,280
above the camera maximum or below the camera minimum,

100
00:03:55,280 --> 00:03:58,000
you know, helps make sure that, you know,

101
00:03:58,000 --> 00:03:59,600
you're always in a quantitative range

102
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:01,400
when that's important.

103
00:04:01,400 --> 00:04:02,360
Yeah, yeah.

104
00:04:02,360 --> 00:04:07,160
It can also be the intensity metrics and or, you know,

105
00:04:07,160 --> 00:04:09,000
saturation percent maximal,

106
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:12,480
found those really helpful for when there is some amount

107
00:04:12,480 --> 00:04:15,400
of debris, like fluorescent debris in an image

108
00:04:15,400 --> 00:04:19,440
that accidentally, you know, particularly fibrous sweater

109
00:04:19,440 --> 00:04:22,400
dropping onto your sample someday,

110
00:04:22,400 --> 00:04:25,120
will often be easily flagged.

111
00:04:25,120 --> 00:04:26,800
The images that have, you know,

112
00:04:26,800 --> 00:04:28,920
some chunk of very fluorescent,

113
00:04:28,920 --> 00:04:31,080
something that's not supposed to be there,

114
00:04:31,080 --> 00:04:33,840
will often be easily flagged by those metrics.

115
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:35,960
Great point.

116
00:04:37,480 --> 00:04:39,600
And the last set of metrics are the blur metrics.

117
00:04:39,600 --> 00:04:43,240
So blur can be kind of difficult to define.

118
00:04:43,240 --> 00:04:46,280
So there's a few different mathematical approaches

119
00:04:46,280 --> 00:04:47,720
that are here.

120
00:04:48,720 --> 00:04:52,880
One of them is saying, what is the correlation

121
00:04:52,880 --> 00:04:55,520
within particular areas?

122
00:04:55,520 --> 00:04:59,400
So if I say, if I take a square of, you know, 50 pixels,

123
00:04:59,400 --> 00:05:03,280
how likely is it that all the pixels are the same,

124
00:05:03,280 --> 00:05:04,680
like are highly similar?

125
00:05:06,280 --> 00:05:08,720
Because real biological objects

126
00:05:08,720 --> 00:05:11,160
probably have a lot of variability if they're in focus.

127
00:05:11,200 --> 00:05:15,200
If they're not in focus, they might have more sameness

128
00:05:16,480 --> 00:05:18,400
because they're out of focus.

129
00:05:18,400 --> 00:05:23,400
And so increased correlation can actually mean

130
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:25,400
that your image is blurry.

131
00:05:31,480 --> 00:05:36,480
The focus score sort of operates on a similar principle.

132
00:05:36,560 --> 00:05:41,000
It actually operates based on how much is the variance

133
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:44,560
in the image, the idea being if your image is blurry,

134
00:05:44,560 --> 00:05:47,120
if the amount of like variance across the image

135
00:05:47,120 --> 00:05:50,400
is very little, probably something is wrong.

136
00:05:50,400 --> 00:05:53,840
It's not in focus because real biology sort of jitters.

137
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:58,520
And there's some great citations here for a bunch of these.

138
00:05:58,520 --> 00:06:03,320
That one, they actually compared a whole bunch

139
00:06:03,320 --> 00:06:08,320
of different methods across a whole bunch of,

140
00:06:08,560 --> 00:06:09,400
oh, wrong paper.

141
00:06:10,280 --> 00:06:12,480
No, no, something went wrong, of course.

142
00:06:16,440 --> 00:06:19,480
They actually tried a whole bunch of different methods

143
00:06:20,320 --> 00:06:25,320
and then they tested them across DIC images

144
00:06:25,720 --> 00:06:29,080
and Brightfield and fluorescence and a whole bunch of things.

145
00:06:29,080 --> 00:06:32,840
And actually we're able to say like across all kinds

146
00:06:32,840 --> 00:06:37,840
of different things, like this particular method

147
00:06:38,840 --> 00:06:43,840
often produces really good sort of measurement of blurriness.

148
00:06:46,960 --> 00:06:51,360
So that is what CellProfiler refers to as the focus score.

149
00:06:52,480 --> 00:06:56,880
The local focus score is just that and do it in tiles.

150
00:06:56,880 --> 00:06:59,480
So this is the particular metric we were asked about.

151
00:07:01,320 --> 00:07:06,320
So if I break the image into tiles, maybe parts of it

152
00:07:07,320 --> 00:07:09,800
are in focus and parts of it are out of focus.

153
00:07:12,040 --> 00:07:14,400
And so we can say what is that focus score

154
00:07:14,400 --> 00:07:18,000
across the whole image and then get the focus score

155
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:19,840
for each and take the average.

156
00:07:22,400 --> 00:07:25,680
There's also the power log log slope,

157
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:29,160
which I won't go too deep into the math for,

158
00:07:29,160 --> 00:07:33,400
but basically it goes into the frequency space

159
00:07:33,480 --> 00:07:36,440
of the textures in the image

160
00:07:36,440 --> 00:07:39,240
and then takes the log of a couple of different metrics

161
00:07:39,240 --> 00:07:43,160
and you say what is the slope of these particular lines

162
00:07:43,160 --> 00:07:45,280
of measurements in frequency space?

163
00:07:46,400 --> 00:07:49,320
If you think back to your Fourier optics,

164
00:07:50,160 --> 00:07:53,920
high intensity information or high sort of noise information

165
00:07:53,920 --> 00:07:55,880
is encoded in a different part of frequency space

166
00:07:55,880 --> 00:07:58,880
than like big patterns.

167
00:07:58,880 --> 00:08:03,320
And so the slope of this line actually helps indicate,

168
00:08:04,320 --> 00:08:06,760
if the image is changing a lot,

169
00:08:06,760 --> 00:08:08,520
if the textures change a lot

170
00:08:08,520 --> 00:08:11,720
or if the textures are actually pretty smooth.

171
00:08:11,720 --> 00:08:13,880
So the slope of that line changes.

172
00:08:15,480 --> 00:08:19,920
So, self-prophetic provides you all of these.

173
00:08:21,520 --> 00:08:25,120
And I wanna call up this paper in particular,

174
00:08:25,120 --> 00:08:26,400
which is from the imaging platform

175
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:29,160
from a bit ago now from 2012,

176
00:08:29,160 --> 00:08:32,240
that goes through some quality control workflows

177
00:08:32,240 --> 00:08:33,560
and they actually did a really lovely job

178
00:08:33,560 --> 00:08:35,320
doing some things with synthetic blurring

179
00:08:35,320 --> 00:08:37,640
as well as taking some images

180
00:08:37,640 --> 00:08:39,760
and then like physically,

181
00:08:39,760 --> 00:08:41,040
figuring out the right focal plane

182
00:08:41,040 --> 00:08:45,280
and then going 32 microns below and 32 microns above

183
00:08:45,280 --> 00:08:48,320
to actually do a bunch of measurements to say,

184
00:08:48,320 --> 00:08:51,760
well, like how far out of focus can we be

185
00:08:51,760 --> 00:08:54,160
before we start losing our ability to detect

186
00:08:54,160 --> 00:08:56,840
like our quantitative measurement and things like that

187
00:08:56,840 --> 00:09:01,360
and measuring a bunch of these CellProfiler quality metrics

188
00:09:01,400 --> 00:09:02,640
in these different conditions.

189
00:09:02,640 --> 00:09:04,520
So this is a really nice paper.

190
00:09:07,080 --> 00:09:08,320
And we in fact have,

191
00:09:08,320 --> 00:09:10,080
and we'll put a link in the show notes,

192
00:09:10,080 --> 00:09:15,080
a tutorial for looking at image quality

193
00:09:15,360 --> 00:09:18,360
in CellProfiler that sort of uses some of these

194
00:09:18,360 --> 00:09:19,840
measurement quality metrics.

195
00:09:20,920 --> 00:09:23,320
But a couple of things that I wanna point out

196
00:09:25,440 --> 00:09:26,720
are just that,

197
00:09:28,720 --> 00:09:30,880
generally speaking, when you are doing these,

198
00:09:30,880 --> 00:09:33,320
it's hard to draw hard cutoffs.

199
00:09:33,320 --> 00:09:36,760
It's hard to say like one of the sort of

200
00:09:38,360 --> 00:09:40,800
counter examples to that is you might be able

201
00:09:40,800 --> 00:09:42,120
to draw a hard cutoff and say,

202
00:09:42,120 --> 00:09:46,320
if more than 2% of my images is saturated,

203
00:09:46,320 --> 00:09:48,760
I think there's too much saturation.

204
00:09:48,760 --> 00:09:52,280
I can't get good quantification of intensity from here.

205
00:09:52,280 --> 00:09:54,600
You know, I don't want this image anymore.

206
00:09:54,600 --> 00:09:57,640
But for things like blurring and things like correlation,

207
00:09:57,640 --> 00:10:00,200
especially channel to channel,

208
00:10:00,200 --> 00:10:01,800
these things can be really different

209
00:10:01,800 --> 00:10:03,240
and certainly experiment to experiment.

210
00:10:03,240 --> 00:10:06,360
And they can be affected by things like confluency

211
00:10:07,720 --> 00:10:10,680
because that will change the amount of intensity variation

212
00:10:10,680 --> 00:10:12,040
in your image.

213
00:10:12,040 --> 00:10:15,000
So usually we're not so much looking for a hard cutoff

214
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:17,200
as we're looking for the outliers.

215
00:10:18,520 --> 00:10:23,600
So this is some CellProfiler analyst data

216
00:10:23,600 --> 00:10:28,600
from the CellProfiler quality control tutorial.

217
00:10:28,600 --> 00:10:31,560
And here we're looking at one of the image quality metrics,

218
00:10:31,560 --> 00:10:34,320
which is correlation in the ER channel

219
00:10:34,320 --> 00:10:36,600
at a scale of 20 pixels.

220
00:10:36,600 --> 00:10:38,760
The higher this number is,

221
00:10:38,760 --> 00:10:41,760
the more likely we think there might be a focal problem.

222
00:10:42,560 --> 00:10:47,240
And so we can check a really low image.

223
00:10:47,240 --> 00:10:50,720
For some reason, all of these look bad in linear scale.

224
00:10:52,280 --> 00:10:55,360
That looks indeed like a perfectly fine image.

225
00:10:55,360 --> 00:11:00,240
And then something with a really high value.

226
00:11:04,560 --> 00:11:06,840
That indeed looks like a blurry image.

227
00:11:06,840 --> 00:11:07,800
Yeah, totally.

228
00:11:07,800 --> 00:11:12,440
One cannot deny that that image could be better.

229
00:11:14,760 --> 00:11:18,120
But here's the next highest one.

230
00:11:18,120 --> 00:11:22,160
And this doesn't strike me as terribly blurry.

231
00:11:22,160 --> 00:11:24,720
There's a sort of out of focus-y guy

232
00:11:24,720 --> 00:11:27,720
or like piece of debris there.

233
00:11:27,720 --> 00:11:29,600
Let's check the other one.

234
00:11:29,600 --> 00:11:31,800
But so this is where I say,

235
00:11:31,800 --> 00:11:34,680
it can be really difficult to define exactly what's the cutoff

236
00:11:34,680 --> 00:11:38,360
because this is the second highest well.

237
00:11:38,360 --> 00:11:41,680
And this is fine, but this one is clearly not.

238
00:11:41,680 --> 00:11:42,520
Yeah.

239
00:11:44,600 --> 00:11:48,640
And to my point about channels,

240
00:11:48,640 --> 00:11:52,040
so here, for example, is that power log slope

241
00:11:52,040 --> 00:11:55,200
metric across two different channels,

242
00:11:55,200 --> 00:11:57,600
the nuclear channel and the Golgi channel.

243
00:11:58,520 --> 00:12:00,280
And the first thing I'll draw your attention to

244
00:12:00,280 --> 00:12:02,920
is just the scales of these are different.

245
00:12:02,920 --> 00:12:06,040
And even like this central blob here

246
00:12:06,040 --> 00:12:09,020
is not like perfectly on a diagonal.

247
00:12:10,840 --> 00:12:12,480
There is some scatter around here

248
00:12:12,480 --> 00:12:14,440
that the power log log slope in one channel

249
00:12:14,440 --> 00:12:17,440
versus the other might be different.

250
00:12:18,400 --> 00:12:21,040
We can look at some of the outliers here.

251
00:12:23,040 --> 00:12:28,000
And say, yep, this image sure looks terrible.

252
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:30,520
It's basically empty.

253
00:12:30,520 --> 00:12:32,800
So clearly this is a bad image.

254
00:12:35,240 --> 00:12:37,040
But some of these,

255
00:12:45,200 --> 00:12:50,200
they might just be perfectly analyzable

256
00:12:51,080 --> 00:12:52,440
but a little bit empty.

257
00:12:56,880 --> 00:12:59,680
Or they might have a different metric

258
00:12:59,680 --> 00:13:02,560
just because of a little piece of debris

259
00:13:02,560 --> 00:13:06,960
that's off to the edge that wouldn't for me say,

260
00:13:06,960 --> 00:13:10,080
I'm totally uninterested in this image.

261
00:13:11,960 --> 00:13:14,080
I would just say, maybe I wanna mask

262
00:13:14,080 --> 00:13:15,680
that part of the image out.

263
00:13:17,720 --> 00:13:18,640
And it's hard, right?

264
00:13:18,640 --> 00:13:21,040
Because we always want to try to figure out

265
00:13:21,040 --> 00:13:23,520
how we can keep most of our data in.

266
00:13:23,520 --> 00:13:27,360
Nobody takes data just so that they can throw it away.

267
00:13:30,320 --> 00:13:32,560
That's not why we spend all of this time

268
00:13:32,560 --> 00:13:35,080
sort of lovingly doing all these experiments

269
00:13:35,080 --> 00:13:36,240
only to throw them away.

270
00:13:37,480 --> 00:13:41,760
So I just wanna do one more here.

271
00:13:41,760 --> 00:13:45,000
Oh, I didn't mean to move that.

272
00:13:45,880 --> 00:13:48,760
Which is to show the one that Erin mentioned

273
00:13:48,760 --> 00:13:50,400
which is percent maximal.

274
00:13:51,920 --> 00:13:56,240
Cause that we can definitely use to find things like debris.

275
00:13:58,760 --> 00:14:00,720
Yep, there we go.

276
00:14:00,720 --> 00:14:02,280
That's a big old piece of debris.

277
00:14:02,280 --> 00:14:03,640
That should not be there.

278
00:14:05,520 --> 00:14:09,280
But these metrics can all help.

279
00:14:09,280 --> 00:14:11,320
They can certainly be used to find things

280
00:14:11,320 --> 00:14:15,320
but they can be really hard to sort of set hard limits on.

281
00:14:16,280 --> 00:14:18,440
You can certainly decide to sort of say,

282
00:14:18,440 --> 00:14:20,720
I'm gonna make a central clump based on some metrics

283
00:14:20,720 --> 00:14:22,240
that I've checked in my data.

284
00:14:23,160 --> 00:14:28,160
But for things like how consistent is the data

285
00:14:28,360 --> 00:14:30,280
for different channels,

286
00:14:30,280 --> 00:14:32,720
maybe really different for a nuclear channel

287
00:14:32,720 --> 00:14:34,920
where we know it's not gonna be fully confluent

288
00:14:34,920 --> 00:14:36,240
and a cell membrane channel

289
00:14:36,240 --> 00:14:38,600
where we know if the cells are fully confluent,

290
00:14:38,600 --> 00:14:41,000
there will be no background present in the image.

291
00:14:41,120 --> 00:14:43,520
So we should be careful about setting hard cutoffs

292
00:14:43,520 --> 00:14:45,720
and we should be careful about sort of

293
00:14:45,720 --> 00:14:47,760
overly relying on these metrics

294
00:14:48,720 --> 00:14:51,200
because they can be really hard to interpret.

295
00:14:51,200 --> 00:14:54,000
But used carefully, they can help you identify

296
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:56,240
some of the real problems in your image.

297
00:14:56,240 --> 00:14:59,280
And if you do the self-proferred quality control tutorial,

298
00:14:59,280 --> 00:15:01,200
you can see how you can create classifiers

299
00:15:01,200 --> 00:15:04,040
to throw them out if you do find hard limits

300
00:15:04,040 --> 00:15:07,160
that work for you for your particular data set,

301
00:15:07,160 --> 00:15:08,920
for your particular day.

302
00:15:08,960 --> 00:15:12,880
Yeah, I think also what I found really interesting

303
00:15:12,880 --> 00:15:17,080
is I think, okay, this is over time,

304
00:15:17,080 --> 00:15:20,960
how we have used these QC metrics has changed.

305
00:15:20,960 --> 00:15:25,840
I think some of that is changes in the field

306
00:15:25,840 --> 00:15:28,080
and some of it is changes in the microscopy, right?

307
00:15:28,080 --> 00:15:32,040
So we've found like the data sets that we are given now

308
00:15:32,040 --> 00:15:36,320
are often have less debris and focus issues

309
00:15:36,320 --> 00:15:38,080
than they used to, right?

310
00:15:38,480 --> 00:15:41,320
Just autofocus on microscopes is better

311
00:15:41,320 --> 00:15:44,160
than it was in 2012, right?

312
00:15:44,160 --> 00:15:47,440
Things have changed technology-wise there.

313
00:15:47,440 --> 00:15:51,920
So we are much less likely to get a giant set of images

314
00:15:51,920 --> 00:15:55,200
in which there is a systematic focus issue,

315
00:15:56,080 --> 00:16:00,360
meaning we are less reliant on actually pulling out

316
00:16:00,360 --> 00:16:02,760
bad images from our data.

317
00:16:02,760 --> 00:16:07,600
And I think we have also sort of moved then a lot further

318
00:16:07,640 --> 00:16:12,640
from whole image rules and QC and filtering

319
00:16:14,640 --> 00:16:18,960
into looking at the single cell level and saying,

320
00:16:18,960 --> 00:16:23,960
okay, I've got some single cells like at the cellular level

321
00:16:24,360 --> 00:16:26,800
where my measurements are crazy far off.

322
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:30,120
And maybe it's because, oh, this cell was totally out of focus

323
00:16:30,120 --> 00:16:33,560
or this cell was underneath a giant piece of debris

324
00:16:33,560 --> 00:16:35,120
and filtering that way.

325
00:16:35,160 --> 00:16:37,880
But that requires a level of compute

326
00:16:39,200 --> 00:16:44,200
that we, again, was totally different in access in 2012.

327
00:16:44,480 --> 00:16:49,480
And so even what, not that I joined the lab in 2012,

328
00:16:50,760 --> 00:16:55,120
but even when I joined the lab in 2019, right?

329
00:16:55,120 --> 00:16:58,960
What we do now as common practice versus then

330
00:16:58,960 --> 00:17:01,800
is still even shifted.

331
00:17:01,800 --> 00:17:02,640
Yeah.

332
00:17:03,640 --> 00:17:05,520
So all of that is a very long way to say,

333
00:17:05,520 --> 00:17:09,880
I'm not sure exactly what the local focus score

334
00:17:09,880 --> 00:17:12,520
being different for a particular phenotype means for you.

335
00:17:12,520 --> 00:17:13,840
It could be something as different

336
00:17:13,840 --> 00:17:15,720
as it's changing the confluence.

337
00:17:15,720 --> 00:17:19,840
And so this metric, which says how consistent is,

338
00:17:19,840 --> 00:17:23,640
you know, a particular region in its intensity

339
00:17:23,640 --> 00:17:25,480
and then averaging that across the whole thing,

340
00:17:25,480 --> 00:17:27,760
maybe there are more regions that are empty

341
00:17:27,760 --> 00:17:29,600
or more regions that are full.

342
00:17:29,680 --> 00:17:33,040
And therefore we're changing this value.

343
00:17:33,040 --> 00:17:34,240
It could be something like that.

344
00:17:34,240 --> 00:17:38,320
It could be that it's changing the height of your cell,

345
00:17:38,320 --> 00:17:41,760
which is making it sort of be out of focus

346
00:17:41,760 --> 00:17:45,040
like or seem more out of focus, even though it is in focus.

347
00:17:45,040 --> 00:17:47,160
There's a lot of things that this could be,

348
00:17:48,200 --> 00:17:53,200
but there's a lot of ways you can use this data.

349
00:17:54,160 --> 00:17:56,600
It can just be a little hard to interpret.

350
00:17:56,600 --> 00:17:57,440
Yeah.

351
00:17:58,440 --> 00:18:00,520
I think that's everything I wanted to say

352
00:18:00,520 --> 00:18:01,640
about quality control.

